<HEAD>Education Secretary Issues Recommended Reading List for Kids</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   What should children read in elementary school?
   Secretary of Education William J. Bennett provided his own
suggested reading list in ``James Madison Elementary School,'' his
report on a model elementary elementary curriculum this week
   Here are some of his choices:
   For children in kindergarten through grade 3:
   ``Behind the Back of the Mountain: Black Folktales from Southern
Africa,'' Verna Aardema.
   ``Aesop for Children.''
   ``Hans Christian Andersen's Fairy Tales.''
   ``Wiley and the Hairy Man,'' Molly Bang.
   ``Once in Puerto Rico,'' Pura Belpre.
   Madeline books, Ludwig Bemelmans.
   ``The Three Billy Goats Gruff,'' Susan Blair.
   ``The Pied Piper of Hamelin,'' Robert Browning.
   ``The Story of Babar, the Little Elephant,'' Jean de Brunhoff.
   The Ramona and Henry Huggins books, Beverly Cleary.
   ``Adventures of Pinocchio,'' Carlo Collodi.
   ``The Courage of Sarah Noble,'' Alice Daigliesh.
   ``Book of Nursery and Mother Goose Rhymes,'' Marguerite De
Angeli.
   ``The Whipping Boy,'' Sid Fleischman.
   ``The Three Bears,'' retold by Paul Galdone.
   ``Grimm's Fairy Tales.''
   ``The Wonder Book,'' Nathaniel Hawthorne.
   ``Little Red Riding Hood,'' retold by Trina Schart Hyman.
   ``John Henry: An American Legend'' and ``The Snowy Day,'' Ezra
Jack Keats.
   ``Just So Stories,'' Rudyard Kipling.
   ``The Arabian Nights'' and ``Aladdin and the Wonderful Lamp,''
Andrew Lang.
   Pippi Longstocking books, Astrid Lindgren.
   ``Frog and Toad Together,'' Arnold Lobel.
   ``Mrs. Piggle-Wiggle,'' Betty MacDonald.
   ``Make Way for Ducklings and Blueberries for Sal,'' Robert
McCloskey.
   ``Winnie-the-Pooh,'' A. A. Milne.
   ``Amelia Bedelia,'' Peggy Parish.
   ``Cinderella,'' Charles Perrault.
   ``The Tale of Peter Rabbit,'' Beatrix Potter.
   ``Clementine,'' Robert Quackenbush.
   Curious George books, H. A. Rey.
   ``Where the Wild Things Are,'' Maurice Sendak.
   ``The Cat in the Hat,'' Dr. Seuss.
   ``Noah's Ark,'' Peter Spier.
   ``Sylvester and the Magic Pebble,'' William Steig.
   ``A Child's Garden of Verses,'' Robert Louis Stevenson.
   ``Brian Wildsmith's Illustrated Bible Stories,'' Philip Turner.
   ``Charlotte's Web,'' E. B. White.
   Little House books, Laura Ingalls Wilder.
   ``The Velveteen Rabbit,'' Margery Williams.
   ``Rumpelstiltskin,'' retold by Paul O. Zelinsky.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   For children in grades 4 through 6:
   ``Born Free,'' Joy Adamson.
   ``Little Women,'' Louisa May Alcott.
   ``Sounder,'' William H. Armstrong.
   ``Peter Pan,'' J. M. Barrie.
   ``Charlie and the Chocolate Factory,'' Roald Dahl.
   ``The Black Stallion,'' Walter Farley.
   Great Brain books, John D. Fitzgerald.
   ``Johnny Tremain,'' Esther Forbes.
   Selections from ``Poor Richard's Almanack,'' Benjamin Franklin.
   ``Lincoln: A Photobiography,'' Russell Freedman.
   ``And Then What Happened, Paul Revere?,'' Jean Fritz.
   ``A Swinger of Birches: Poems of Robert Frost for Young People.''
   ``The Wind in the Willows,'' Kenneth Grahame.
   ``Mythology,'' Edith Hamilton.
   ``The People Could Fly: American Black Folk Tales,'' Virginia
Hamilton.
   ``Misty of Chincoteague,'' Marguerite Henry.
   ``The Phantom Tollbooth,'' Norton Juster.
   ``The Jungle Book'' and ``Captains Courageous,'' Rudyard Kipling.
   ``Lassie Come-Home,'' Eric Knight.
   ``Tales from Shakespeare,'' Charles and Mary Lamb.
   The Rainbow Fairy books, Andrew Lang.
   ``A Wrinkle in Time,'' Madeleine L'Engle.
   ``The Lion, the Witch, and the Wardrobe,'' C. S. Lewis.
   ``The Call of the Wild,'' Jack London.
   ``Paul Bunyan Swings His Axe,'' Dell J. McCormick.
   ``Bridge to Terabithia'' and ``The Great Gilly Hopkins,''
Katherine Paterson.
   ``Tales of Mystery and Imagination,'' Edgar Allan Poe.
   ``The Merry Adventures of Robin Hood,'' Howard Pyle.
   ``Bambi,'' Felix Salten.
   ``Abe Lincoln Grows Up'' and ``Rootabaga Stories,'' Carl
Sandburg.
   ``Black Beauty,'' Anna Sewell.
   ``A Day of Pleasure: Stories of a Boy Growing up in Warsaw,''
Isaac Bashevis Singer.
   ``Heidi,'' Johanna Spyri.
   ``Treasure Island,'' Robert Louis Stevenson.
   ``The Nutcracker: A Story and a Ballet,'' Ellen Switzer.
   ``What's the Big Idea, Ben Franklin?,'' Margot Tomes.
   ``Swiss Family Robinson,'' Johann Wyss.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   For grades 7 and 8:
   ``I Know Why the Caged Bird Sings,'' Maya Angelou.
   ``Alice's Adventures in Wonderland,'' Lewis Carroll.
   ``The Red Badge of Courage,'' Stephen Crane.
   ``Madame Curie: A Biography,'' Eve Curie.
   ``Robinson Crusoe,'' Daniel Defoe.
   ``Great Expectations,'' Charles Dickens.
   ``I'm Nobody! Who Are You?,'' Emily Dickinson.
   ``Adventures of Sherlock Holmes,'' Arthur Conan Doyle.
   ``The Count of Monte Cristo'' and ``The Three Musketeers,''
Alexandre Dumas.
   ``Washington: The Indispensable Man,'' James Thomas Flexner.
   ``Diary of a Young Girl,'' Anne Frank.
   ``A Raisin in the Sun,'' Lorraine Hansberry.
   ``The House of Seven Gables,'' Nathaniel Hawthorne.
   ``The Old Man and the Sea,'' Ernest Hemingway.
   ``The Gift of the Magi and Other Stories,'' O. Henry.
   ``Kon-Tiki,'' Thor Heyerdahl.
   ``The Legend of Sleepy Hollow'' and ``Rip Van Winkle,''
Washington Irving.
   ``Story of My Life,'' Helen Keller.
   ``Kim,'' Rudyard Kipling.
   ``To Kill a Mockingbird,'' Harper Lee.
   ``Mutiny on the Bounty,'' Charles Nordhoff and J.N. Hall.
   ``The Scarlet Pimpernel,'' Baroness Emma Orczy.
   ``The Complete Tales and Poems,'' Edgar Allan Poe.
   ``The Chosen,'' Chaim Potok.
   ``The Yearling,'' Marjorie Kinnan Rawlings.
   ``The Little Prince,'' Antoine de Saint-Exupery.
   ``Ivanhoe,'' Sir Walter Scott.
   Plays and sonnets, William Shakespeare.
   ``Frankenstein,'' Mary Shelley.
   ``The Red Pony'' and ``The Pearl,'' John Steinbeck.
   ``The Strange Case of Dr. Jekyll and Mr. Hyde,'' Robert Louis
Stevenson.
   ``The Adventures of Tom Sawyer,'' Mark Twain.
   ``20,000 Leagues Under the Sea,'' Jules Verne.
   ``Up From Slavery,'' Booker T. Washington.
   ``The Time Machine,'' H. G. Wells.
   ``Ethan Frome,'' Edith Wharton.
   ``The Sword in the Stone,'' T. H. White.
   ``The Bridge of San Luis Rey,'' Thornton Wilder.
   ``The Virginian,'' Owen Wister.
</TEXT>
